00:25:52.440 --> 00:25:55.679
Can you reach every link,
button, and form field?

00:25:55.680 --> 00:25:57.269
Can you close a pop-up?

00:25:57.270 --> 00:25:58.979
Can you complete a checkout?

00:25:58.980 --> 00:26:02.249
If you can't, neither can
your customers who depend

00:26:02.250 --> 00:26:03.930
on keyboard access.

00:26:04.140 --> 00:26:07.859
In e-commerce, that means
lost sales, frustrated users,

00:26:07.860 --> 00:26:11.699
and potential lawsuits,
because it's not just a code issue,

00:26:11.700 --> 00:26:15.689
it's a barrier that stops someone
from buying your product.

00:26:15.690 --> 00:26:17.819
Now let's talk about
inaccessible forms.

00:26:17.820 --> 00:26:21.089
One of the most common
and most damaging barriers online.

00:26:21.090 --> 00:26:23.779
Forms power everything
we do on the web.

00:26:23.780 --> 00:26:25.699
They're how customers check out,

00:26:25.700 --> 00:26:29.699
subscribe to a newsletter,
create an account, or request help.

00:26:29.700 --> 00:26:30.809
In e-commerce,

00:26:30.810 --> 00:26:34.649
a single inaccessible form
can block an entire transaction.

00:26:34.650 --> 00:26:37.619
Here's what happens
when accessibility is missing.

00:26:37.620 --> 00:26:40.259
If a field has no programmatic label,

00:26:40.260 --> 00:26:42.959
screen reader users
don't know what to enter.

00:26:42.960 --> 00:26:46.019
If error messages aren't
linked to the correct field,

00:26:46.020 --> 00:26:48.059
they can't tell what needs fixing.

00:26:48.060 --> 00:26:50.579
If the form can't be completed
with the keyboard,

00:26:50.580 --> 00:26:53.009
many users can't submit it at all.

00:26:53.010 --> 00:26:54.869
Accessibility in forms means

00:26:54.870 --> 00:26:57.389
that every input
must have a proper label,

00:26:57.390 --> 00:27:00.484
and placeholders
do not count as labels.

00:27:00.780 --> 00:27:03.869
Required fields
must be clearly identified.

00:27:03.870 --> 00:27:07.829
Errors must be announced and
associated with the correct field,

00:27:07.830 --> 00:27:11.429
describing what's wrong
and what needs to be entered.

00:27:11.430 --> 00:27:13.619
The full form, from start to submit,

00:27:13.620 --> 00:27:16.079
must be operable
with the keyboard alone.

00:27:16.080 --> 00:27:19.919
Because when a form fails,
it's not just a technical issue.

00:27:19.920 --> 00:27:22.829
It's a lost opportunity,
a blocked purchase,

00:27:22.830 --> 00:27:26.009
a missed sign-up,
or a denied application.

00:27:26.010 --> 00:27:29.919
Under the ADA and WCAG,
these aren't just usability bugs,

00:27:29.920 --> 00:27:32.699
they're barriers
to equal participation.

00:27:32.700 --> 00:27:35.759
Test every form on your site,
whether it's a checkout page

00:27:35.760 --> 00:27:38.999
or a one-field newsletter
sign-up, ask yourself,

00:27:39.000 --> 00:27:41.219
can it be completed without a mouse?

00:27:41.220 --> 00:27:43.379
Can every user
understand what's required

00:27:43.380 --> 00:27:45.419
and fix errors independently?

00:27:45.420 --> 00:27:49.499
If not, the form isn't just broken,
it's excluding some people,

00:27:49.500 --> 00:27:53.489
and that's just the kind of violation
that lands in lawsuits.

00:27:53.490 --> 00:27:55.559
Next up is inaccessible videos,

00:27:55.560 --> 00:27:58.499
and this one carries major weight,
because video is one

00:27:58.500 --> 00:28:01.829
of the most powerful tools
businesses use to communicate,

00:28:01.830 --> 00:28:04.475
to sell, to inspire, to connect.

00:28:04.800 --> 00:28:08.609
When accessibility is missing,
it becomes one of the most common

00:28:08.610 --> 00:28:11.369
and costly barriers
cited in lawsuits.

00:28:11.370 --> 00:28:14.099
The first issue is missing captions.

00:28:14.100 --> 00:28:18.749
When captions are absent, deaf
and hard-of-hearing users lose access

00:28:18.750 --> 00:28:22.559
to the spoken message,
the dialogue, the instructions,

00:28:22.560 --> 00:28:25.529
maybe even the emotion
that drives engagement.

00:28:25.530 --> 00:28:30.089
Captions aren't optional,
they're required for equal access.

00:28:30.090 --> 00:28:33.209
The second barrier
is no text descriptions.

00:28:33.210 --> 00:28:35.429
Think about short product clips,

00:28:35.430 --> 00:28:38.369
a model turning
to show how a jacket fits,

00:28:38.370 --> 00:28:40.949
a demo showing how software looks,

00:28:40.950 --> 00:28:44.429
a close-up of fabric texture,
any kind of video

00:28:44.430 --> 00:28:48.397
where there's no sound,
no narration, just visuals,

00:28:48.480 --> 00:28:51.671
these need a text description,
because without it,

00:28:51.672 --> 00:28:55.469
blind users are excluded from
the information that's being shown.

00:28:55.470 --> 00:28:57.629
In lawsuits, these
videos are often cited

00:28:57.630 --> 00:29:00.929
because they deny equal
access to product details

00:29:00.930 --> 00:29:02.639
and brand storytelling,

00:29:02.640 --> 00:29:06.449
key information that cited
users receive instantly.

00:29:06.450 --> 00:29:07.859
The fix is simple.

00:29:07.860 --> 00:29:10.889
Add captions to every video
with spoken content.

00:29:10.890 --> 00:29:13.829
Add text descriptions
to videos without narration,

00:29:13.830 --> 00:29:17.400
so visuals are equally
conveyed through words.

00:29:17.610 --> 00:29:19.169
Every clip tells a story.

00:29:19.170 --> 00:29:22.499
You just want to make sure
everyone can get it.

00:29:22.500 --> 00:29:25.019
Let's look at one more,
low color contrast.

00:29:25.020 --> 00:29:27.299
This one doesn't just
affect people with low vision,

00:29:27.300 --> 00:29:28.739
it affects everyone.

00:29:28.740 --> 00:29:32.819
Think about when you've seen light
gray text on a white background.

00:29:32.820 --> 00:29:35.489
That can be really hard to see
for some users.

00:29:35.490 --> 00:29:37.859
I was just editing a video recently,

00:29:37.860 --> 00:29:40.349
and the control bar
at the bottom was so faint,

00:29:40.350 --> 00:29:41.939
it was almost invisible.

00:29:41.940 --> 00:29:45.272
That lack of contrast
made the task harder.

00:29:45.450 --> 00:29:49.409
On a website, that same
issue can become a barrier.

00:29:49.410 --> 00:29:51.629
When the text blends
into the background,

00:29:51.630 --> 00:29:53.789
people can't easily
read your content,

00:29:53.790 --> 00:29:56.729
navigate your menus,
or use your forms.

00:29:56.730 --> 00:29:58.889
When that happens, users leave,

00:29:58.890 --> 00:30:00.779
or if they can't leave
because they need

00:30:00.780 --> 00:30:03.899
to complete something,
it becomes a source of frustration.

00:30:03.900 --> 00:30:07.649
You can absolutely design
something beautiful and on-brand.

00:30:07.650 --> 00:30:09.539
You just need to ensure
your colors meet

00:30:09.540 --> 00:30:12.634
the contrast ratios
that WCAG specifies.

00:30:12.750 --> 00:30:15.899
Often, it's as simple
as adjusting a hex code slightly

00:30:15.900 --> 00:30:19.769
to stay compliant while keeping
your look consistent.

00:30:19.770 --> 00:30:23.339
Remember, low color
contrast isn't just a design flaw.

00:30:23.340 --> 00:30:27.389
It's one of the most common issues
cited in accessibility lawsuits.

00:30:27.390 --> 00:30:30.839
These five examples
represent only a small portion

00:30:30.840 --> 00:30:34.769
of the violations repeatedly
cited in accessibility litigation.

00:30:34.770 --> 00:30:37.979
Each constitutes a barrier
that excludes users

00:30:37.980 --> 00:30:41.369
and creates measurable
legal exposure for businesses.

00:30:41.370 --> 00:30:44.699
Addressing accessibility
is not merely a best practice,

00:30:44.700 --> 00:30:47.279
it's a legal obligation
and a critical safeguard

00:30:47.280 --> 00:30:50.930
for compliance, usability,
and brand integrity.

00:30:50.940 --> 00:30:52.739
We've covered the law, the lawsuits,

00:30:52.740 --> 00:30:54.509
and the most common violations.

00:30:54.510 --> 00:30:56.639
Now it's time
to bring it all together.

00:30:56.640 --> 00:30:58.169
Here's what you can do.

00:30:58.170 --> 00:31:00.029
Test your website thoroughly.

00:31:00.030 --> 00:31:03.059
You can't fix what you
haven't identified.

00:31:03.060 --> 00:31:05.879
Automated scans are a helpful start,
but they only catch

00:31:05.880 --> 00:31:08.039
a fraction of accessibility barriers.

00:31:08.040 --> 00:31:09.719
The issues that trigger lawsuits

00:31:09.720 --> 00:31:12.269
are often the ones those tools miss.

00:31:12.270 --> 00:31:15.719
Combine automated checks
with manual testing to uncover

00:31:15.720 --> 00:31:19.290
the full picture,
then remediate those issues.

00:31:19.740 --> 00:31:21.329
Involve disabled users.

00:31:21.330 --> 00:31:24.139
Hire people with disabilities
to test your site.

00:31:24.140 --> 00:31:28.499
Screen reader users, keyboard-only
users, low-vision users.

00:31:28.500 --> 00:31:32.099
Their feedback provides authentic,
real-world insights

00:31:32.100 --> 00:31:36.067
that mirror the experiences
documented in lawsuits.

00:31:36.300 --> 00:31:39.209
There are helpful tools
you can use in WordPress,

00:31:39.210 --> 00:31:41.499
like Joel Dolson's
Accessibility Plugin

00:31:41.500 --> 00:31:44.039
and Equalize Digital's
Accessibility Checker.

00:31:44.040 --> 00:31:47.249
These can help you identify
and address barriers.

00:31:47.250 --> 00:31:50.555
Finally, follow
the recognized legal standard.

00:31:50.556 --> 00:31:55.900
WCAG 2.1 Level AA is the technical
standard currently in the ADA.

00:31:56.310 --> 00:31:58.019
Now what you can't do.

00:31:58.020 --> 00:32:00.629
You can't assume
your website is accessible

00:32:00.630 --> 00:32:03.149
just because your theme claims it is.

00:32:03.150 --> 00:32:07.019
Even accessibility-ready WordPress
themes still require testing,

00:32:07.020 --> 00:32:12.119
and page builders can override
that code, introducing new barriers.

00:32:12.120 --> 00:32:15.479
You can't treat accessibility
as a one-time project.

00:32:15.480 --> 00:32:19.049
Every update to WordPress core,
page builders, themes,

00:32:19.050 --> 00:32:22.769
or plugins can introduce
new accessibility barriers.

00:32:22.770 --> 00:32:25.259
That's why ongoing testing is vital.

00:32:25.260 --> 00:32:28.769
In fact, DOJ settlement
agreements often require

00:32:28.770 --> 00:32:32.699
businesses to test
their websites every six months.

00:32:32.700 --> 00:32:34.409
You can't rely on widgets.

00:32:34.410 --> 00:32:36.509
They don't bring
your site into compliance

00:32:36.510 --> 00:32:38.909
and often create additional barriers.

00:32:38.910 --> 00:32:40.649
Compliance isn't static.

00:32:40.650 --> 00:32:43.903
It's maintained
through consistent action.

00:32:44.130 --> 00:32:46.829
After everything we've covered,
the lawsuits, the rulings,

00:32:46.830 --> 00:32:50.789
the violations, the big question is,
where is this all heading?

00:32:50.790 --> 00:32:55.079
In April 2024, the Department
of Justice updated the ADA,

00:32:55.080 --> 00:32:56.939
requiring all public entities

00:32:56.940 --> 00:32:59.549
to make their websites
and apps accessible.

00:32:59.550 --> 00:33:03.041
That's now a clear deadline
and no gray area.

00:33:03.180 --> 00:33:05.429
But private businesses
are still navigating

00:33:05.430 --> 00:33:07.799
a maze of lawsuits and unclear rules.

00:33:07.800 --> 00:33:09.509
That might soon change.

00:33:09.510 --> 00:33:15.435
In May 2025, a bipartisan group
in Congress introduced H.R. 3417,

00:33:15.477 --> 00:33:18.879
the Websites and Software
Applications Accessibility Act.

00:33:18.880 --> 00:33:21.359
It's still in committee,
but if it passes,

00:33:21.360 --> 00:33:25.139
it will rewrite the rules
for every business in America.

00:33:25.140 --> 00:33:28.649
This bill would cover
public-facing websites and apps,

00:33:28.650 --> 00:33:31.377
including online-only businesses.

00:33:31.380 --> 00:33:33.239
It would close legal loopholes

00:33:33.240 --> 00:33:35.669
that have fueled
confusion and litigation.

00:33:35.670 --> 00:33:39.719
It would establish clear nationwide
standards aligned with WCAG.

00:33:39.720 --> 00:33:42.449
And it would require
updates every three years

00:33:42.450 --> 00:33:45.149
so the law keeps
pace with technology.

00:33:45.150 --> 00:33:47.939
For the first time,
enforcement would be unified,

00:33:47.940 --> 00:33:49.979
shared between
the Department of Justice

00:33:49.980 --> 00:33:52.619
and the Equal Employment
Opportunity Commission,

00:33:52.620 --> 00:33:57.029
giving businesses a clear roadmap
and a standard to follow.

00:33:57.030 --> 00:34:01.709
More than a regulatory shift,
this marks a civil rights milestone.

00:34:01.710 --> 00:34:04.169
Once this law passes,
digital accessibility

00:34:04.170 --> 00:34:06.239
won't just be best practice.

00:34:06.240 --> 00:34:09.059
It will be recognized
for what it truly is,

00:34:09.060 --> 00:34:12.149
a right to information,
a right to participation,

00:34:12.150 --> 00:34:16.439
a right to access, and that's
where the future is headed.

00:34:16.440 --> 00:34:18.839
While Congress continues
to debate federal standards,

00:34:18.840 --> 00:34:21.809
some states have begun
taking action on their own,

00:34:21.810 --> 00:34:24.779
targeting patterns of abusive
website accessibility litigation

00:34:24.780 --> 00:34:28.259
that overwhelm small
businesses with repetitive lawsuits.

00:34:28.260 --> 00:34:31.830
In 2023, Kansas became
the first state to pass

00:34:31.860 --> 00:34:35.699
the Act Against Abusive
Website Access Litigation.

00:34:35.700 --> 00:34:37.859
This law allows Kansas businesses

00:34:37.860 --> 00:34:40.709
or the Attorney General
to sue the plaintiff

00:34:40.710 --> 00:34:44.339
or attorney when lawsuits
are deemed predatory.

00:34:44.340 --> 00:34:47.099
Other states are now
following Kansas' lead.

00:34:47.100 --> 00:34:49.740
In 2025, Illinois introduced

00:34:49.800 --> 00:34:52.889
the Stop Abusive
Website Access Litigation Act,

00:34:52.890 --> 00:34:55.019
granting the Attorney
General authority

00:34:55.020 --> 00:34:57.839
to bring civil actions
against parties or firms

00:34:57.840 --> 00:35:02.309
that repeatedly file meritless
website accessibility claims.

00:35:02.310 --> 00:35:05.879
These laws, however,
do not block legitimate cases.

00:35:05.880 --> 00:35:07.589
They preserve
the right of individuals

00:35:07.590 --> 00:35:09.989
with disabilities
to pursue valid claims,

00:35:09.990 --> 00:35:12.659
but they aim to curb
bad-faith filings

00:35:12.660 --> 00:35:15.689
that do little
to advance accessibility.

00:35:15.690 --> 00:35:17.489
Together, these state
measures reflect

00:35:17.490 --> 00:35:20.639
a growing call for balance,
ensuring access remains

00:35:20.640 --> 00:35:25.139
a civil right while protecting
businesses from abuse of process.

00:35:25.140 --> 00:35:28.169
As more states act,
the pressure builds for a clear,

00:35:28.170 --> 00:35:31.829
unified federal standard, precisely
what the Websites and Software

00:35:31.830 --> 00:35:35.718
Applications Accessibility
Act seeks to establish.

00:35:35.940 --> 00:35:38.789
After all the lawsuits, laws,
loopholes, and lessons,

00:35:38.790 --> 00:35:41.021
it comes down to one thing.

00:35:41.340 --> 00:35:43.739
Make your website and app accessible,

00:35:43.740 --> 00:35:48.299
not out of fear of litigation,
not as a checkbox for compliance,

00:35:48.300 --> 00:35:50.879
